{"aligned_page": 5, "alignment_score": 0.24392097264437687, "char_end_0based": 1712, "char_start_0based": 19, "clean_redaction_id": null, "decision": "excluded", "failed_tests": ["full_page_or_admin"], "original_redaction_id": 6, "page_tag": "[PAGE 05]", "pair_key": "3160442_CIA-RDP79T00975A003000420001-1", "recut_action": "kept_after_recut", "recut_from_original": true, "recut_reason": "noncontent_document_furniture,noncontent_footer_date_phrase,noncontent_page_reference", "red_gap_text": "", "red_gap_token_count": 0, "red_source_page": 4, "row_kind": "match", "segment_id": 1, "tests": {"full_page_or_admin": {"details": {"alignment_score": 0.24392097264437687, "candidate_token_total": 281, "coverage": 0.996454, "red_admin_stub": true, "red_token_count": 7, "row_kind": "match", "thresholds": {"full_page_coverage": 0.95, "low_alignment_score": 0.25, "min_full_page_tokens": 50}, "unred_token_count": 282}, "passed": false}, "noncontent_keyword": {"details": {"admin_token_ratio": 0.0369, "date_only": false, "has_measurement": false, "has_route_pair": false, "has_weird_map_line_symbol": false, "map_hint_count": 0, "map_legend_like": false, "matched_map_phrases": [], "matched_phrases": ["comment on", "general"], "near_page_edge": true, "recut_reason": "noncontent_document_furniture,noncontent_footer_date_phrase,noncontent_page_reference", "removed_by_recut": false, "short_numeric_or_garbled": false, "short_section_heading": false}, "passed": true}, "nonempty_redacted_alternate_conflict": {"details": {"conflict_reasons": [], "page_candidate_coverage": 0.996454, "red_gap_text": "", "red_gap_token_count": 0, "thresholds": {"alternate_length_multiplier": 3, "long_alternate_min_red_gap_tokens": 20, "near_full_page_coverage": 0.9, "short_candidate_max_tokens": 10, "short_span_max_tokens": 5, "short_span_nontrivial_alternate_min_red_gap_tokens": 2}, "token_count": 271}, "passed": true}, "ocr_equivalent_to_redacted_text": {"details": {"length_ratio": null, "reason": "missing_red_gap", "red_gap_text": "", "similarity": null}, "passed": true}, "short_span_min_tokens": {"details": {"min_tokens": 2, "token_count": 271}, "passed": true}}, "text": "JORDAN\n\nComment on: Deployment on 8 April of armored cars and infantry elements of the Jordanian army's 10th Armored Brigade to cover the approaches to Amman appears to have been undertaken by ultranationalist army officers to discourage King Hussain from attempting to dismiss army chief of staff Nuwar and the leftist-dominated cabinet of Prime Minister Nabulsi. Supporters of Nuwar and the cabinet had apparently learned of Hussain's plans to take action against them on 9 April. According to press reports from Amman on 9 April, the cabinet had been in a night-long meeting attended by General Nuwar.\n\nHussain did not order the deployment of troops around Amman, which had been reported as a \"routine training exercise.\" Although Hussain professed confidence that they would not move against him, Nuwar and the ultranationalist \"free officers\" had advised Hussain that the army would not support him against popular demonstrations which would break out if the cabinet were changed. These troop movements will therefore probably forestall hasty action by Hussain. He would have no chance of successful action without army support.\n\nShould Hussain now attempt to appeal directly to loyal army units against the \"free officers,\" a breakdown in internal order could occur which would invite moves by Israel, and possibly Iraq, on Jordan.\n\nSaudi Arabia and Syria presently each have over 3,000 troops in Jordan. At the time of the termination of Britain's responsibilities to defend Jordan, on 13 March, about 1,300 British troops--including a tank battalion--were deployed in South Jordan near Aqaba. Evacuation of these forces has begun and is scheduled to be completed in the next few months", "token_count": 271, "token_end_0based": 273, "token_start_0based": 3, "token_text": "jordan comment on deployment on 8 april of armored cars and infantry elements of the jordanian army's 10th armored brigade to cover the approaches to amman appears to have been undertaken by ultranationalist army officers to discourage king hussain from attempting to dismiss army chief of staff nuwar and the leftist-dominated cabinet of prime minister nabulsi supporters of nuwar and the cabinet had apparently learned of hussain's plans to take action against them on 9 april according to press reports from amman on 9 april the cabinet had been in a night-long meeting attended by general nuwar hussain did not order the deployment of troops around amman which had been reported as a routine training exercise although hussain professed confidence that they would not move against him nuwar and the ultranationalist free officers had advised hussain that the army would not support him against popular demonstrations which would break out if the cabinet were changed these troop movements will therefore probably forestall hasty action by hussain he would have no chance of successful action without army support should hussain now attempt to appeal directly to loyal army units against the free officers a breakdown in internal order could occur which would invite moves by israel and possibly iraq on jordan saudi arabia and syria presently each have over 3 000 troops in jordan at the time of the termination of britain's responsibilities to defend jordan on 13 march about 1 300 british troops including a tank battalion were deployed in south jordan near aqaba evacuation of these forces has begun and is scheduled to be completed in the next few months", "unred_source_page": 5}
